We recommended and Management agreed to: 

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis of the dormant receivable account and validate the same by sending formal demand letters to those identified accountable officers/debtors/implementing agencies to settle their long-outstanding accounts or at least prove the non-recoverability of the accounts; 

Exert efforts and exhaust legal remedies to recover/settle/liquidate the receivables whose accountable officers/recipient can still be traced or are still connected with the agency, and the fund transfers from other LGUs and NGAs;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to coordinate with source agencies of fund transfers to facilitate immediate return of excess or unutilized funds; and

Consider request of write-off for the dormant account as a last resort.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Continue to prioritize the implementation of the projects/programs/activities outlined in the AIP for the calendar year;

Exert efforts to expedite the implementation of remaining five (5) unimplemented PPAs;

Provide specific timeline for the processing of documents including efficient monitoring of its status to address issues that may cause delays in the processing;

Consider the conduct of early procurement activities that will address the delays caused by late bidding; and

Consider augmentation of personnel handling monitoring and supervising the implementation of projects ensuring timely execution and completion.

a) For the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to:
i. direct the concerned department/personnel to ensure the full and proper implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, draw the necessary accounting entries, and adhere to the presentation and disclosure requirements, as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
ii. assign additional personnel to the GSO to strengthen and enhance their efficiency and capacity in meeting the growing demands of the proper upkeep of the Municipality’s properties;
b) For the General Services Office to sharpen their controls and improve procedures for managing the Municipality’s properties and equipment. Among the physical controls that may be adopted by the Office are the following:
i. conduct a proper physical count of properties at least annually and prepare a comprehensive RPCPPE, ensuring that all relevant information are accurately recorded and aligned with accounting records;
ii. prepare and maintain necessary semi-expendable property reports, ledgers and monitoring, as outlined in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
iii. established a formalized inventory system with clearly defined responsibilities for property custodians, and conduct regular updates, ensuring that all required reports and ledgers are kept. This will help ensure the accuracy of property and inventory records, streamline asset tracking, reduce the risk of loss or mismanagement, and ensure compliance with the relevant provisions of COA Circulars and regulations.
c) For the Municipal Accounting Office to improve account reporting by adhering to the guidelines of IPSAS 31 by disclosing the required data for each class of Intangible Assets, especially the nature and amount of any change in value that has a material effect in the current reporting period or is expected to have a material effect in subsequent periods;
d) For the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to ensure that the balances of the PPE accounts are reconciled on a regular basis, that any discrepancies noted shall be immediately investigated and resolved, and that appropriate adjustments are made to maintain the proper valuation of accounts.
Furthermore, both Offices shall collaborate their efforts and practice regular coordination to warrant a more accurate report of PPE balances.

a. Coordinate with the concerned departments to ensure effective planning, implementation and reporting of PPAs and evaluate the feasibility of each PPA on a regular basis. If considered not feasible, reprogram into other appropriate projects that better meet the community’s evolving needs;
