c. Prepare and submit the Utilization Report for both current and continuing appropriations to the Auditor’s Office on a regular basis for periodic monitoring of planned PPAs; and
d. Consider specifying the implementation date in the AIP to guide the management when to prepare the necessary documents and actions to be needed in the implementation.

a. Evaluate the necessary requirements of the PPAs to determine whether they are feasible and if not, may submit status reports to the SA providing details and terms for possible return of the remaining funds to be used for other projects that can help improve the locality or if the said fund may be transferred to the General Fund as available for the LGU’s disposition, otherwise the same be remitted to the SA to be cleared from the books of accounts;
b. Consider appointing a focal person for each project or implementing office to streamline the prompt implementation of PPAs;
c. Strengthen internal control mechanisms to improve project implementation efficiency and ensure delivery of services to the recipient public while adhering to the rules and regulations concerning fund transfers, including liquidations.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following measures:
Require the GSO to request copies of the supporting transfer documents from the DENR-EMB and  inquire about the cost of the subject equipment as the basis of recording in the books of accounts and other LGU records, and further ensure that proper documentation is obtained for all future donations received;
Require an Inventory Appraisal Committee to be tasked with appraising the fair value of the donated property to establish the fair market value should the source agency fail to provide the cost of the said equipment;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record all grants and donations, whether in cash or in kind from other government agencies and instrumentalities in the books of the period the transactions occurred; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the necessary Journal Entries to recognize the donated equipment from the DENR-EMB and record the corresponding depreciation in order to present fairly the financial statement.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
a. 	Require the Personnel/Human Resource Management Officer to maximize the use of digitalization in the recording and monitoring of employees' leave cards;
b. 	Direct the HRMO to conduct audit of the employee's leave card prior to the processing of terminal leave benefits;
c. 	Require the retired officials and employees to refund the excess amount claimed on their terminal leave benefits, and for the LGU to make checks payable to the underpaid employees; and
Instruct the HRMO and Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the documentary requirements embodied under Section 5.13 of COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to monitor and expedite the implementation of the remaining projects under the 20% LDF to adequately deliver the basic services to the constituents and maximize its benefits to the intended beneficiaries in compliance with the provisions of Section 5 of DILG-DBM Circular No. 2017-01 and RA No. 7160 through the following remedial measures;
Submit a justification letter for the non-implementation/ delayed completion of the projects, and a plan of action to be carried out by the concerned officials; and
Expedite/mobilize the MPDC and other concerned offices in the early planning and implementation of development projects to avoid incurring unnecessary costs caused by inflation resulting from delayed implementation.

We recommended and the management assured compliance to the following:
