e.) Contract of Lease to follow the standards/guidelines provided under COA Circular No. 88-282A which provides for the Uniform Standards/Guidelines to Determine the Reasonableness of the terms of lease contracts to ensure that the interests of both parties are protected and ambiguities and/or misunderstanding can be avoided.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the proponents headed by Municipal Planning and Development Officer, Municipal Agriculturist Officer and the Municipal Engineer to conduct thorough planning in coming up with timely implementation of proposed projects;
Instruct the heads of the implementing offices to prioritize and expedite the implementation of these projects to provide the expected benefits to the intended beneficiaries on time and maximum use of the programs/projects, and to act promptly on issues or constraints causing the non-implementation of the projects;
Make representation with the Department of Agriculture on its intention to purchase land as organic demo farm out of the collections made on its Plant Now Pay Later project;
Require the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Agriculturist to provide the updated status report of the projects, submit MOA and other pertinent documents to the Audit Team for review; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to return the unused amount of fund transfer or dormant accounts to the source agency.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the MEEDO thru the Municipal Treasurer to issue demand letters for the collection of default rental fees as mandated by the Section 12, Title 3 of the Municipal Ordinance No. 01-12, an ordinance enacting a Market Code of the Municipality of Lala, Lanao del Norte stating the duties and functions of MEEDO to coordinate and cooperate with the Municipal Treasurer on matters of collection and imposition of fees and charges;
Terminate the contract of lessees who failed to pay monthly rental for a period of three (3) consecutive months;
Require the MEEDO to justify the names of payor with actual payments made for CY 2020 but not included in the official list of stallholders as of December 2020;
Require the MEEDO to prepare and submit Monthly Report of Collection starting CY 2021 to the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant for the proper performance monitoring and recording of receipts;
Require the MEEDO to submit to the audit team and the Municipal Treasurer updated and completely filled up Contract of Leases of stallholders as well incorporating in the contract the imposition of corresponding surcharges in cases of default payment;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to establish a system of collection to enforce the collection of arcade rental fees periodically and demand collection of the unpaid rental fees. The Municipal Treasurer should also maintain an individual subsidiary ledgers of the arcade stall lessees for easy monitoring and enforcing collection and strict implementation of the Contract of Lease;
Create the necessary positions in the Lala Public Arcade for effective and efficient delivery of the needed services in its operations; and
Submit to the audit team any amendments regarding the change in the monthly rentals of the stallholders stated in the Tax Ordinance which should be formally deliberated by the Sanggunian and go through public hearing to avoid future violations.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the concerned collector, Ms. Elsa D. Biaco, to remit daily the collections to the Municipal Treasurer/Liquidating Officer including the proper accomplishment of Daily Statement of Collections and Accountable Forms (DSCAF);
Require the Municipal Treasurer to review the existing internal control system regarding the cash management in the Treasurer’s Office;
Require the Municipal Treasurer, who has a direct supervision over the collectors, to strictly implement the applicable rules and regulations to safeguard the assets of the Municipality;
Demand the Municipal Treasurer to effect the full use and function of E-TRACS of LGU Lala as a tool to help define proper accountability and responsibility of the collectors especially in the real time generation of reports pertaining to accountable forms inventory, collection, remittance, liquidation and deposit; and
Provide additional field collectors in order support the existing manpower in the collections.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Demand the MSWDO to reinforce the compliance of DSWD Memorandum Circular No. 11, Series of 2019 particularly in the strict implementation of assistance to individuals in crisis situation;
Refrain from reimbursing cash assistance to individuals without following the proper implementing procedures in the grant of assistance to individuals in crisis situation;
Require the MSWDO to submit the lacking documentary requirements of the 16 reimbursement of cash assistance mentioned in the above observation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Should assess its existing organizational structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established, thereby, avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel;

Should instruct the Human Resource & Management Officer to refrain from employing Job Order/Service Contract personnel whose nature were in the administrative, clerical or utility functions and hire Job Order/Service Contract personnel based on necessity and intended only for identified and attributed local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months;

Should incorporate these job order/service contract personnel to the vacant positions in the official plantilla of LGU personnel subject to the rules and regulations of Civil Service Commission on the 2017 Omnibus Rules on Appointments and Other Human Resource Actions, Revised 2018 to properly match that of the needs of the LCE or any other officials needing assistance thereof;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to support disbursements of funds for services rendered by job order and service contract personnel with the necessary and appropriate supporting documents such as Contract of Services or Memorandum of Agreement (MOA), approved accomplishment reports & DTRs to establish validity and propriety of payments; and

Require every job order and service contract personnel to enroll in the biometric scan system of the LGU to monitor their arrival to and departure from their office and to maintain record of attendance of the personnel in their respective assignments and offices to vouch the authenticity of their daily presence at workplace. In case the personnel is assigned in the field, require the Head of Office to issue a Travel Order to justify his assignment.

